Plutarch illusio: The Lyre-sung Nome was established long before the F lute-sung, in the days of Terpander . . . Terpander composed Lyre-sung Proems in epic verse, and it is clear that the ancient Lyre-sung Nomes were of this nature from the practice of Timotheus, who sang his first nomes in hexameters with an intermixture of dithyrambic phraseology, so that he might conceal at the outset his sins against the musical tradition.

Proclus Chrestomalhy: The Nome is in honour of Apollo and takes its name srom his appellation Nomius.3 The ancients used to make choi-uses and sing the Nome to flute or lyre, but Chrysothemis the Cretan first adopted a distinctive dress, and taking a lyre in his hand to represent Apollo, sang a nome solo, and as he became famous for this performance
